  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Inscription on Transcribing the Lotus Sutra in Gold Characters
  author: Shi Wuwei
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The Buddha's compassion knows no obstruction, dispensing teachings according to circumstance without error. The power of the Dharma transcends conception, swiftly transforming fortune into longevity. How then could I not pour forth earnest devotion and humbly beseech the profound grace?

    I, the disciple, possess no cultivation of concentration and wisdom, yet undeservedly receive the courtesies of teacher and guest. Wishing to repay the sovereign's exceptional kindness, I have long offered humble prayers with sincere heart. Now, taking the silver bestowed upon me, I have purchased gold leaf and transcribed this most venerable Lotus Sutra. I have established a platform for the dharma gathering, where as the true teachings are recited, each character flows with golden light, and as enlightenment's brilliance illuminates, each wave cradles the moon's reflection. Such an offering as this is no common deed.

    I humbly pray: May the sovereign swiftly receive the deep grace of the One Vehicle and the secret protection of the Three Bodies. May blessings ever descend through the nine gates with renewed imperial favor. May the royal procession swiftly return to the Three Kingdoms with flourishing fortune everlasting. Where the true wind blows, may all withered things return to life.
  footnotes:
    - 'The One Vehicle (一乘): A fundamental Mahayana Buddhist concept referring to the universal path to Buddhahood taught in the Lotus Sutra.'
    - 'Three Bodies (三身): The trikaya in Buddhist philosophy—the Dharmakaya (Law Body), Sambhogakaya (Enjoyment Body), and Nirmanakaya (Transformation Body).'
    - 'Three Kingdoms (三韓): A classical reference to the ancient Korean kingdoms of Goguryeo, Baekje, and Silla, used here to refer to Korea.'
    - 'Nine Gates (九闥): A poetic reference to the imperial palace''s gates, suggesting the highest levels of court.'
